+
+---
+
+## Step 1: Choose your demo path
+
+<ask_followup_question>
+<question>What would you like to try?</question>
+<options>["🚀 Full Run-Through — All features in sequence", "💬 Briefing — Read and discuss project status", "📝 Documents — Create, edit, and store", "🌐 Live Data — Fetch real data from the internet"]</options>
+</ask_followup_question>
+
+If the user picks a specific path, skip to the relevant steps:
+- "Full Run-Through" → continue with Step 2
+- "Briefing" → go to Step 2, then skip to Step 7
+- "Documents" → go to Step 3
+- "Live Data" → go to Step 6
+
+Track which sections were actually executed during this run. In Step 7, only mark completed capabilities that were truly demonstrated.
+
+---
+
+## Step 2: Morning Briefing — Persistent Memory
+
+Read the .resonance/ files you just created and give the user a morning briefing. This demonstrates that Resonance remembers context across sessions.
+
+Summarize what you found in a brief, friendly "Good Morning" standup format:
+- **Done last time**: What was completed last session
+- **🔴 Overdue items**: Call out overdue tasks (especially the invitations)
+- **Open tasks**: What else is still pending
+- **Key insights**: Any lessons from memory that are relevant today
+- **Recommendation**: Strongly recommend booking the location and sending invitations ASAP
+
+Keep it conversational. End this step with the following question:
+
+<ask_followup_question>
+<question>The invitations are overdue and the location needs to be booked this week. Shall we tackle the invitations?</question>
+<options>["📝 Yes, let's draft the invitation!", "📋 Tell me more about the options first"]</options>
+</ask_followup_question>
+
+**STOP HERE.** Do not continue to Step 3 until the user responds. This is a mandatory pause point.
+
+---
+
+## Step 3: Create a Document — Invitation Draft
+
+Now we create a document from scratch. This demonstrates file creation with AI assistance.
+
+Say to the user: "Let's create a document to showcase this capability. I'll draft the party invitation."
+
+Create the file \`invitation_draft.md\` with:
+- **Event**: Sarah's 30th Birthday Party
+- **Date & Time**: The Saturday date from the state file, 7:00 PM
+- **Location**: Osteria Bella Vista (recommend the top choice from the research)
+- **What to expect**: Italian dinner, drinks, music, good vibes
+- **Dress code**: Smart casual
+- **RSVP**: By [2 weeks from today]
+- **Note about vegetarian options**
+
+Make it warm and personal — this is for friends and family, not a corporate event. Keep it under 30 lines.
+
+After creating the file, tell the user: "This is the first draft. In the next step, you can add your own touch."
+
+---
+
+## Step 4: Your Contribution — Human + AI Together
+
+This step demonstrates the human-in-the-loop workflow. The user adds their own content.
+
+<ask_followup_question>
+<question>Now it's your turn! What would you like to add to the invitation?</question>
+<options>["🎉 Personal Message — A few words from the heart for Sarah", "🗺️ Directions — How to get there (public transport, parking)", "🎁 Gift Info — Coordinate a group gift", "✍️ Something else — I'll write my own addition"]</options>
+</ask_followup_question>
+
+Based on the user's choice:
+- If they pick a predefined option, ask them to provide 2-3 bullet points of content for that section
+- If they pick "Something else", ask them what they want to add
+
+Then add their section to \`invitation_draft.md\`. After adding the section, end with this question:
+
+<ask_followup_question>
+<question>Your section has been added! Now I can polish the whole invitation — shall I improve and finalize it?</question>
+<options>["✨ Yes, polish it!", "👍 Looks good as is, skip to the next feature"]</options>
+</ask_followup_question>
+
+**STOP HERE.** Do not continue to Step 5 until the user responds.
+If the user chooses to skip, jump to Step 6.
+
+---
+
+## Step 5: AI-Assisted Editing & Comparison
+
+This step demonstrates AI-assisted editing. Resonance edits the document in-place — the user sees the diff directly in the editor (built-in diff view).
+
+Now improve \`invitation_draft.md\`:
+- Tighten the language — make it warmer and more inviting
+- Improve the formatting and flow
+- If the user's added section has rough edges, polish it while keeping their meaning intact
+- Add a small personal touch (e.g., a fun line about celebrating Sarah)
+
+Tell the user what you changed and why. Be specific: "I made X changes: ..."
+
+Point out to the user: "You can see the changes directly in the editor as a diff — you can accept or reject each change individually. This is the normal workflow with Resonance."
+
+After the user accepts the edits, save the final version to the docs folder with proper frontmatter:
+
+Create the file \`docs/invitation_sarah_30th.md\` with the improved content, adding YAML frontmatter at the top:
+
+\`\`\`yaml
+---
+summary: Party invitation for Sarah's 30th birthday — date, location, dress code, RSVP
+read_when:
+  - "Work on Sarah's birthday party"
+  - "Send invitations"
+last_updated: [today's date]
+---
+\`\`\`
+
+Then explain to the user:
+"Resonance saves finished documents in \`docs/\` — with a frontmatter header that describes what it's about and when to read it. The next time you open a chat about the party, Resonance automatically finds and reads this document. No knowledge is lost."
+
+End this step with a transition question:
+
+<ask_followup_question>
+<question>The document is saved! Ready to see the next feature?</question>
+<options>["🌐 Yes, show me Live Data!", "⏭️ Skip to the summary"]</options>
+</ask_followup_question>
+
+**STOP HERE.** Do not continue to Step 6 until the user responds.
+If the user chooses "Skip to the summary", jump directly to Step 7.
+
+---
+
+## Step 6: Fetching Live Data — API Integration
+
+This step shows that Resonance can pull live data from the internet — not just work with local files.
+
+First, briefly explain the terminal:
+"In a moment, a **Terminal** will open at the bottom — that's a command line where Resonance can execute commands. You don't need to type anything there; I'll do it for you. If it bothers you, you can close it anytime with the **X** in the top right corner of the terminal window."
+
+Then say:
+"I'll now show you how Resonance can fetch live data from the internet — for example, weather data, exchange rates, or information about a country. This works with any public or internal interface (API)."
+
+<ask_followup_question>
+<question>What live data should we fetch?</question>
+<options>["🌤️ Weather — Current weather for the party location", "💱 Exchange Rates — Current EUR rates", "🎓 Fun Fact — A random fact for the party", "🌍 Look up a Country — Info about a country"]</options>
+</ask_followup_question>
+
+Based on the choice, run the appropriate command:
+- Weather: Ask the user for a city (suggest the party city). Use Open-Meteo (free, no API key):
+  \`curl -s "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=48.14&longitude=11.58&current_weather=true"\` (default: Munich)
+  Look up the city's coordinates if they name a different city. Parse the JSON and present it as a human-readable weather report.
+- Exchange Rates:
+  \`curl -s "https://open.er-api.com/v6/latest/EUR"\`
+  Pick the 5 most relevant currencies (USD, GBP, CHF, JPY, PLN) and present them as a clean table.
+- Fun Fact:
+  \`curl -s "https://uselessfacts.jsph.pl/api/v2/facts/random?language=en"\`
+  Present the fact and suggest how it could be used as an icebreaker at the party.
+- Look up a Country: Ask the user for a country name:
+  \`curl -s "https://restcountries.com/v3.1/name/{country}?fields=name,capital,population,currencies,languages,flag"\`
+  Present the data as a structured profile.
+
+Present the results in a clear, non-technical way. No raw JSON — always interpret and format the data as a short, readable summary.
+
+After presenting the results, say:
+"That was real live data from the internet. Resonance can connect to any interface — public or internal — and integrate the results directly into your workflow."
+
+---
+
+## Step 7: End of Day — Session Continuity
+
+This is the final step. Demonstrate how Resonance saves context for the next session.
+
+Say: "To wrap up, I'll show you how Resonance saves progress for the next session."
+
+Read the current state file, then update \`.resonance/01_state.md\` by adding a section at the bottom:
+
+\`\`\`
+## Demo Session — [today's date]
+- ✅ [Only include items that were actually run in this session]
+- 💡 Next time: [suggest something relevant based on what happened]
+\`\`\`
+
+Important:
+- Do not claim steps that were skipped.
+- If only one branch was run, write a short branch-specific closing summary.
+- If the full path was run, use the full recap.
+
+Then give a closing summary:
+
+"That was the demo! Here's what you saw:
+
+1. **Memory** — I read the project status and gave a briefing
+2. **Document Creation** — We created a party invitation from scratch
+3. **Collaboration** — You contributed your own section
+4. **Editing with Preview** — I improved the document — you could accept or reject each change individually
+5. **Knowledge Management** — The finished document was stored in \`docs/\` to be automatically found in future chats
+6. **Live Data** — We fetched real data from the internet and presented it in an understandable way
+7. **Saving Progress** — Everything is saved — next time we chat, I'll know where we left off"
+
+End with:
+"**The demo is now complete.** 🎉
+
+To start with a real task, just open a **new chat** (+ icon at the top) and briefly describe what you want to work on — for example:
+
+- *'I need a concept for a client project'*
+- *'Help me structure a presentation'*
+- *'Summarize this document'*
+
+Resonance automatically remembers the context across all chats. Have fun!"
+</explicit_instructions>\n
+`
